node.text: Soaking up the last few days of summer 🥃

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by The Bourbon Enthusiast on September 16, 2021 tagging @jimbeamofficial, and @basilhayden. May be an image of drink and indoor.

node.text: Light and easy with notes of vanilla cream, zesty cinnamon, and lingering caramel. Out of the Basil Hayden lineup, this “Toast” would be the one I’m reaching for 🥃

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by The Bourbon Enthusiast on September 15, 2021. May be an image of drink and indoor.

node.text: If you’re a fan of the Dickel profile, their new 8-year bourbon will surely be in your wheelhouse. It brings the signature mineral/vitamin notes you’d typically get from a Dickel whiskey, along with maple spice, nutty vanilla, caramel corn, and toffee notes. A very easy sipper and a solid age statement, but could stand to be a higher proof 🥃

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by The Bourbon Enthusiast on September 14, 2021. May be an image of drink.

node.text: At 120 proof, this Barton 1792 sourced bourbon hits with a blast of burnt sugar, followed by honey and moderate oak. If the rest of Kirkland’s single barrels are this good, count me in 👍

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by The Bourbon Enthusiast on September 13, 2021 tagging @brownforman. May be an image of bottle.

node.text:
King of Kentucky is returning this year with the release of its fourth edition.  Coming in September, this will be the fourth release for the brand. “While the majority of this year’s volume will remain in Kentucky, the expression will also be available in limited quantities in Illinois and Ohio.

The 2021 expression will be a 14-year old Kentucky Straight Bourbon, and will produce approximately 2,700 bottles. 

King of Kentucky was established in 1881 as a Kentucky Straight Bourbon Whiskey.  Brown-Forman acquired the brand in 1936 from Selected Kentucky Distillers and, by 1940, converted it to a blended whiskey until it was discontinued in 1968.  In 2018, Brown-Forman revived the lapsed label paying homage to the brand’s past.

King of Kentucky is an annual/on-going periodic release of a single barrel inventory featuring a barrel-strength, minimally-filtered proof presentation, with each release and every barrel being unique.  For this year’s iteration, Master Distiller Chris Morris chose 33 barrels to set aside for the limited-release product.”

- @brownforman

node.text:
It’s been over 100 years since Jack Daniel’s offered a 10-year. The extra aging and increased oak notes make this a welcomed addition to their lineup. The pour brings the classic notes of sweet corn and dried fruits you’d expect from a Jack Daniel’s whiskey, coupled with soft oak, caramelized sugar and hints of maple spice. Batch one of the 10-year is hitting shelves this month and will be released annually on a limited basis. 

———————————————————————————

node.text:
Four Roses’ 2021 Limited Edition Small Batch launches in September

“Latest release is highest proof in the Limited Edition series, featuring barrels aged 12 to 16 years.

Four Roses Distillery will issue the newest release in its series of limited-quantity special bottlings this September – the 2021 Limited Edition Small Batch.

Non-chill filtered and bottled at 114.2 proof, the 2021 Limited Edition Small Batch features four different hand-selected batches aged 12 to 16 years. These batches represent four of the distillery’s 10 distinct Bourbon recipes – a 16-year-old Bourbon from the OBSV recipe, a 14-year-old OBSQ, a 12-year-old OESK, and a 16-year-old OESV. “

- @fourrosesbourbon 

———————————————————————————
